                <head>413. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On November 13, Ambassador Slim met with Under Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> to discuss the U.S. decision not to
                    grant Tunisia a loan for the Oued Nebana project. <persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                        >Dillon</persName> assured <persName corresp="#p_SM2">Slim</persName> the
                    United States had not made a final decision and was reevaluating the project in
                    light of new information. He also explained the technical and legal difficulties
                    it presented. A memorandum of this conversation is in Department of State,
                    Central Files, 772.5–<gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/11–1659. Its substance
                    was sent to Tunis in telegram 633, November 16. (<hi rend="italic"
                    >Ibid.</hi>)</p>
                <p>Clarence <persName>Randall</persName>, Chairman of the Council on Foreign
                    Economic Policy, arrived in Tunis on December 7, where he and his party were
                    briefed on the Tunisian economic situation, December 7–8, by the Embassy staff.
                    Reports on his trip are in Eisenhower Library, CFEP Records, Office of the
                    Chairman, and in a Special Staff Note, January 12; <hi rend="italic">ibid.,</hi>
                    Whitman File, <persName>Eisenhower</persName> Diaries.</p>
            </div>
